| Notes                   = * The Externals shares a psychic-link with each other that allows them to not only sense each other and where, but can call on each other at will from great distances.{{r|Excalibur Vol 4 11}}{{r|Excalibur Vol 4 12}} But also when one rises from the dead and when one is killed by another External.{{r|X-Force #9|10}}{{r|X-Force #53}}{{r|Cable Vol 1 150}}{{r|Cable Vol 1 152|154}} This ability seems stronger with the eldest among the Externals.

* It was revealed that the Externals can only die at the hands of a fellow External, and in doing so that External absorbs the essence of their brethren gaining godhood.{{r|X-Force #53|54}}{{r|Cable #153|154}}
** But when an External kills another and fails to kill all the other Externals, he/she losses the power they gained and the fallen Externals come back to life.{{r|X-Force #54}}{{r|Cable #150}}{{r|Cable #151}}{{r|Cable #154}}

* Whether or not [[Samuel Guthrie (Earth-616)|Cannonball]] is an External remains a point of contention.{{r|X-Men: Future History: Messiah War Sourcebook #1}} Sam Guthrie's future versions, including a conversation with Graymalkin where we learn that Cannonball lived well into the 24th century,{{r|X-Force #10}} were shown to survive into the future. Besides this, the other Externals also sensed that Cannonball was one of them.{{r|X-Force #10}}

* When answering [[Doop (Earth-616)|Doop]], Cable stated that Cannonball wasn't an External and that it was only a rumor.{{r|Cable Vol 1 151}} The ambiguity of Cannonball's status as an External was used as a source of humor years later. After he rapidly recovered from a Purifier attack, one of the X-Men's students, [[David Alleyne (Earth-616)|David]], asked Beast about it, and McCoy said Sam was immortal. David admitted after witnessing Cannonball's resurrection that he wasn't sure if McCoy was joking or not.{{r|New X-Men Vol 2 28}}
* The Externals immortality does not become active when their mutant powers do, but rather when they meet their first death.{{r|X-Force #10}}
** This would explain why Nicodemus and Saul, though in incredible shape,{{r|X-Force #20}} are physically older then the rest of their fellow Externals.{{r|X-Force #10}}

| Trivia                  = * At one point it was revealed that each External was claimed to represent an intangible concept: Burke fortitude, Absalom despair, Nicodemus wisdom, Saul patience, Gideon opportunity, Crule ferocity, Candra guile, Selene corruption, and Cannonball hope.{{r|X-Force #37}} Although Apocalypse's concept has yet to be revealed, speculation by fans is it's either destruction or evolution.
* Cable believed the group had gone by both "Externals" and "High Lords", preferring the former over the latter.{{r|X-Force #10}}. Other than Cable calling Cannonball and his future Apocalypse "High Lord",{{r|X-Force #8}}{{r|X-Force #25}} only the six that had banded together called themselves the "High Lords".{{r|X-Force #8|10}}{{r|X-Force #12}}{{r|X-Force #14}}{{r|X-Force #21|22}}{{r|X-Force #25}}{{r|X-Force #37}}
** Though the six had become a type of authority among the other Externals and they possibly used the title High Lords to represent that, the High Lords are not a separate group but a moniker they began using most likely when they started to band together.
** Other than calling Cannonball "High Lord", most likely in hopes he would join them, they have never referred to Selene, Candra, or Apocalypse as such nor have they referred to themselves using that moniker, with the possible exception of Apocalypse.
* The Externals share many similarities with the [[Eternals (Homo immortalis)|Eternals]], mostly similar names and being immortals.

